@EndNode

@Node "Answer" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/Answer"
@Next "ArqString"
@Prev ""
@Toc  "cfgModem"

Name:      Answer=<boolean>

   Forces GMS_Mailer to operate in "answer mode". GMS_Mailer will then wait
for a call, answer the phone and try to start a session with the remote
system.


Example:   Answer=NO

@EndNode

@Node "ArqString" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/ArqString"
@Next "ModemAnswer"
@Prev "Answer"
@Toc  "cfgModem"

Name:      ArqString=<string>

   Tells GMS_Mailer what string the modem returns when it connects to another
modem under an error-control protocol. HST modems, for example, return the
string "ARQ" as in "CONNECT 9600/ARQ/HST/HST".  

   You must setup the correct <ArqString> for your modem when you use
<SniffArq>.


Example:   ArqString=ARQ


See also:     @{"SniffArq" Link "SniffArq"}

@EndNode

@Node "ModemAnswer" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/ModemAnswer"
@Next "ModemInit"
@Prev "ArqString"
@Toc  "cfgModem"

Name:      ModemAnswer=<string>

   This string is sent to the modem whenever GMS_Mailer detects a `RING' and
wants to answer the phone.


Example:   ModemAnswer=ATA|

@EndNode

@Node "ModemInit" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/ModemInit"
@Next "ModemDialPre"
@Prev "ModemAnswer"
@Toc  "cfgModem"

Name:      ModemInit=<string>

   This string will be sent to the modem during the initialization phase of
GMS_Mailer.

- If the modem send `OK' all proceed.
- If the modem send "ERROR" GMS_Mailer exit.


Example:   ModemInit=~~AT~Z~|

@EndNode

@Node "ModemDialPre" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/ModemDialPre"
@Next "ModemDialPost"
@Prev "ModemInit"
@Toc  "cfgModem"

Name:      ModemDialPre=<string>

   This string is sent to the modem whenever GMS_Mailer wants to dial a
number. After sending this string, GMS_Mailer will send the telephone
number to dial, followed by the <ModemDialPost> string.


Example:   ModemDialPre=ATDP


See also:     @{"ModemDialPost" Link "ModemDialPost"}

@EndNode

@Node "ModemDialPost" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/ModemDialPost"
@Next "ModemHangUp"
@Prev "ModemDialPre"
@Toc  "cfgModem"

Name:      ModemDialPost=<string>

   This string is sent to the modem after the telephone number, when
GMS_Mailer wants to dial a number.


Example:   ModemDialPost=|


See also:     @{"ModemDialPre" Link "ModemDialPre"}

@EndNode

@Node "ModemHangUp" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/ModemHangUp"
@Next "SniffArq"
@Prev "ModemDialPost"
@Toc  "cfgModem"

Name:      ModemHangUp=<string>

   This string will be sent to the modem whenever GMS_Mailer wants to hang up
the line.


Example:   ModemHangUp=^|

@EndNode

@Node "SniffArq" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/SniffArq"
@Next ""
@Prev "ModemHangUp"
@Toc  "cfgModem"

Name:      SniffArq=<boolean>

   If you have a modem that will detect MNP, LAP-M, V42 and similar
error-correction protocols, with this keyword, GMS_Mailer will minimize
session-startup delays.


Example:   SniffArq=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "cfgSeriale" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial"
@Next "cfgProtocolli"
@Prev "cfgModem"
@Toc  "MailerSettings"

Serial options
**************

 @{" 7Wire " Link "7Wire"}
 @{" Baud " Link "Baud"}
 @{" Dsr " Link "Dsr"}
 @{" Lock " Link "Lock"}
 @{" MaxBaud " Link "MaxBaud"}
 @{" MinBaud " Link "MinBaud"}
 @{" SerialBufSize " Link "SerialBufSize"}
 @{" SerialName " Link "SerialName"}
 @{" SerialUnit " Link "SerialUnit"}
 @{" SerialFlags " Link "SerialFlags"}
 @{" Shared " Link "Shared"}
 @{" SlowModem " Link "SlowModem"}

@EndNode

@Node "7Wire" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/7Wire"
@Next "Baud"
@Prev ""
@Toc  "cfgSeriale"

Name:      7Wire=<boolean>

   Enable/disable 7-wire cabling. This will instruct the serial device to
use (or not to use) the CTS and RTS signals. If you are using high speed
modems with data compression, such as a US Robotics Courier HST, you must
use <7Wire> handshake and you must set your modem to "hardware handshake"
mode, otherwise various difficulties will arise.


Example:   7Wire=ON

@EndNode

@Node "Baud" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/Baud"
@Next "Dsr"
@Prev "7Wire"
@Toc  "cfgSeriale"

Name:      Baud=<baudrate>

   This is the baudrate to initially talk to the modem -- after power-on or
a reset. This speed may change during a session, when you did not lock the
baudrate.


Example:   Baud=2400


See also:     @{"Lock" Link "Lock"}

@EndNode

@Node "Dsr" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/Dsr"
@Next "Lock"
@Prev "Baud"
@Toc  "cfgSeriale"

Name:      Dsr=<boolean>

   After GMS_Mailer opens the serial.device, it will wait a short while
(depending on <SlowModem>) and then sample the `DSR' line.
If GMS_Mailer doesn't find `DSR' activated, it will report error and
abort.


Example:   Dsr=ON


See also:     @{"SlowModem" Link "SlowModem"}

@EndNode

@Node "Lock" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/Lock"
@Next "MaxBaud"
@Prev "Lock"
@Toc  "cfgSeriale"

Name:      Lock=<boolean>

   Lock the baudrate. If the baudrate is locked, and GMS_Mailer receives a
`CONNECT XXXX' message from the modem, GMS_Mailer will @{B}not@{UB} adjust the
baud rate to XXXX, but continue to operate at the rate specified with the
<Baud> keyword.


Example:   Lock=OFF


See also:     @{"Baud" Link "Baud"}

@EndNode

@Node "MaxBaud" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/MaxBaud"
@Next "MinBaud"
@Prev "Lock"
@Toc  "cfgSeriale"

Name:      MaxBaud=<boolean>

   If turned on, the <MinBaud> parameter will automatically be set to the
baudrate of the called system (found in the nodelist) or the own baudrate
(set with <Baud>) on outgoing calls, whichever is lower.


Example:   MaxBaud=NO


See also:     @{"MinBaud" Link "MinBaud"}

@EndNode

@Node "MinBaud" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/MinBaud"
@Next "SerialBufSize"
@Prev "MaxBaud"
@Toc  "cfgSeriale"

Name:      MinBaud=<minbaud>

   Minimal baudrate to establish a connection. Connections at baud rates
below this limit will not be allowed, no matter if incoming or outgoing.
GMS_Mailer will hang up immediately if the baud rate is lower than the
value specified.


Example:   MinBaud=2400


See also:     @{"ModemHangUp" Link "ModemHangup"}

@EndNode

@Node "SerialBufSize" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/SerialBufSize"
@Next "SerialName"
@Prev "MinBaud"
@Toc  "cfgSeriale"

Name:      SerialBufSize=<bytes>

   This keyword can be used to set the serial receive buffer.


Examples:  SerialBufSize=16000

@EndNode

@Node "SerialName" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/SerialName"
@Next "SerialUnit"
@Prev "SerialBufSize"
@Toc  "cfgSeriale"

Name:      SerialName=<string>

   If you happen to have a modem connected to some other device than the
standard Amiga "serial.device", you can use this parameter to set up the
correct device name. Usually, the default of "serial.device" will just be
about perfect.
For Supra 2400zi modems, use "modem0.device".  


Examples:  SerialName=serial.device
           SerialName=artser.device

@EndNode

@Node "SerialUnit" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/SerialUnit"
@Next "SerialFlags"
@Prev "SerialName"
@Toc  "cfgSeriale"

Name:      SerialUnit=<unit>

   If your modem is connected to some other unit number than zero change this
appropriately.  


Example:   SerialUnit=0


See also:     @{"SerialName" Link "SerialName"}

@EndNode

@Node "SerialFlags" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/SerialFlags"
@Next "Shared"
@Prev "SerialUnit"
@Toc  "cfgSeriale"

Name:      SerialFlags=<flags>

   If you use some other device than "serial.device", you might need to
change this, too. Consult the documentation that came with your other device
or use the default of zero.


Example:   SerialFlags=0


See also:     @{"SerialName" Link "SerialName"}

@EndNode

@Node "Shared" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/Shared"
@Next "SlowModem"
@Prev "SerialFlags"
@Toc  "cfgSeriale"

Name:      Shared=<boolean>

   Open the serial device in shared mode. If you are running GMS_Mailer in
conjunction with a BBS program or similar, you need to switch the serial
device to <Shared=ON> mode, so that both programs can have it open at the same
time.


Example:   Shared=OFF


See also:     @{"SerialName" Link "SerialName"}, @{"SerialUnit" Link "SerialUnit"}

@EndNode

@Node "SlowModem" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/SlowModem"
@Next ""
@Prev "Shared"
@Toc  "cfgSeriale"

Name:      SlowModem=<delay>

   If define the time that GMS_Mailer waits between lowering and raising
of DTR when it tries to reset the modem or hang up, 

   In this version the <delay> value is a multiple of 100 mS.


Example:   SlowModem=10


See also:     @{"Dsr" Link "Dsr"}

@EndNode

@Node "cfgProtocolli" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols"
@Next "cfgSpeciali"
@Prev "cfgSeriale"
@Toc  "MailerSettings"

Protocol options
****************

 @{" ZedZip " Link "ZedZip"}
 @{" ZedZap " Link "ZedZap"}
 @{" DirectZap " Link "DirectZap"}
 @{" Hydra " Link "Hydra"}

 @{" HydraUni " Link "HydraUni"}
 @{" HydraBaud " Link "HydraBaud"}
 @{" HydraString " Link "HydraString"}

@EndNode

@Node "ZedZip" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/ZedZip"
@Next "ZedZap"
@Prev ""
@Toc  "cfgProtocolli"

Name:      ZedZip=<boolean>

   Enable/disable ZedZip mode. ZedZip is the ZModem transfer protocol -- it
will not switch block sizes, but use a fixed block size of 1024 bites. It will
resume an interrupted transfer if possible.


Example:   ZedZip=ON

@EndNode

@Node "ZedZap" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/ZedZap"
@Next "DirectZap"
@Prev "ZedZip"
@Toc  "cfgProtocolli"

Name:      ZedZap=<boolean>

   Enable/disable ZedZap mode. ZedZap is a slight variant of the ZModem
transfer protocol -- on large files, this is one of the fastest protocols
around. ZedZap will automatically switch block sizes depending on modem
speed and quality of the line.
It will also resume an interrupted transfer if possible.


Example:   ZedZap=ON

@EndNode

@Node "DirectZap" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/DirectZap"
@Next "Hydra"
@Prev "ZedZap"
@Toc  "cfgProtocolli"

Name:      DirectZap=<boolean>

   Enable/disable DirectZap mode. DirectZap is a slight variant of the
ZedZap transfer protocol, which is a slight variant of Zmodem -- on large
files, this is the fastest protocol GMS_Mailer has to offer. Like ZedZap,
DirectZap will automatically switch block sizes depending on modem speed
and quality of the line.
It will also resume an interrupted transfer if possible.

Example:   DirectZap=ON

@EndNode

@Node "Hydra" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/Hydra"
@Next "HydraUni"
@Prev "DirectZap"
@Toc  "cfgProtocolli"

Name:      Hydra=<boolean>

   Enable/disable Hydra mode. Hydra is a new bidirectional file transfer
protocol -- on large files, this is the fastest protocol that GMS_Mailer
has to offer. Hydra will automatically switch block sizes depending on
modem speed and quality line.
It will also resume an interrupted transfer if possible.


Example:   Hydra=ON

@EndNode

@Node "HydraUni" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/HydraUni"
@Next "HydraBaud"
@Prev "Hydra"
@Toc  "cfgProtocolli"

Name:      HydraUni=<boolean>

   Enable/disable Hydra to work in unidirectional mode.


Example:   HydraUni=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "HydraBaud" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/HydraBaud"
@Next "HydraString"
@Prev "HydraUni"
@Toc  "cfgProtocolli"

Name:      HydraBaud=<baud>

   Minimal baudrate to enable Hydra file transfer protocol.


Example:   HydraBaud=2400


See also:     @{"Hydra" Link "Hydra"}, @{"HydraString" Link "HydraString"}

@EndNode

@Node "HydraString" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/HydraString"
@Next ""
@Prev "HydraBaud"
@Toc  "cfgProtocolli"

Name:      HydraString=<string>

   Is the string that GMS_Mailer search in connect response to enable Hydra
file transfer protocol.


Example:   HydraString=ARQ


See also:     @{"Hydra" Link "Hydra"}, @{"HydraBaud" Link "HydraBaud"}

@EndNode

@Node "cfgSpeciali" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials"
@Next "cfgSystem"
@Prev "cfgProtocolli"
@Toc  "MailerSettings"

Special options
***************

 @{" BeepDisplay " Link "BeepDisplay"}
 @{" BiSendMail " Link "BiSendMail"}
 @{" BiSendFlo " Link "BiSendFlo"}
 @{" BiSendRlo " Link "BiSendRlo"}
 @{" HoldAll " Link "HoldAll"}
 @{" HoldXMail " Link "HoldXMail"}
 @{" HoldFReqs " Link "HoldFReqs"}
 @{" Pickup " Link "Pickup"}
 @{" ProcessOnly4D " Link "ProcessOnly4D"}
 @{" TaskPri " Link "TaskPri"}

@EndNode

@Node "BeepDisplay" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/BeepDisplay"
@Next "BiSendMail"
@Prev ""
@Toc  "cfgSpeciali"

Name:      BeepDisplay=<boolean>

   GMS_Mailer will flash the screen when the modem send a `CONNECT' message.


Example:   BeepDisplay=ON

@EndNode

@Node "BiSendMail" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/BiSendMail"
@Next "BiSendFlo"
@Prev "BeepDisplay"
@Toc  "cfgSpeciali"

Name:      BiSendMail=<First|Sencond|All>

   With Hydra, specify in which batch GMS_Mailer can send #?.(OUT|CUT|DUT|HUT)
files.


Example:   BiSendMail=All

@EndNode

@Node "BiSendFlo" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/BiSendFlo"
@Next "BiSendRlo"
@Prev "BiSendMail"
@Toc  "cfgSpeciali"

Name:      BiSendFlo=<First|Sencond|All>

   With Hydra, specify in which batch GMS_Mailer can send #?.(FLO|CLO|DLO|HLO)
files.


Example:   BiSendFlo=First

@EndNode

@Node "BiSendRlo" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/BiSendRlo"
@Next "HoldAll"
@Prev "BiSendFlo"
@Toc  "cfgSpeciali"

Name:      BiSendRlo=<First|Sencond|All>

   With Hydra, specify in which batch GMS_Mailer can send #?.RLO files.


Example:   BiSendRlo=First

@EndNode

@Node "HoldAll" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/HoldAll"
@Next "HoldXMail"
@Prev "BiSendRlo"
@Toc  "cfgSpeciali"

Name:      HoldAll=<boolean>


Example:   HoldAll=ON

@EndNode

@Node "HoldXMail" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/HoldXMail"
@Next "HoldFReqs"
@Prev "HoldAll"
@Toc  "cfgSpeciali"

Name:      HoldXMail=<boolean>


Example:   HoldXMail=ON

@EndNode

@Node "HoldFReqs" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/HoldFReqs"
@Next "Pickup"
@Prev "HoldXMail"
@Toc  "cfgSpeciali"

Name:      HoldFReqs=<boolean>


Example:   HoldFReqs=ON

@EndNode

@Node "Pickup" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/Pickup"
@Next "ProcessOnly4D"
@Prev "HoldFReqs"
@Toc  "cfgSpeciali"

Name:      Pickup=<All|Primary|None>

   Select what mail and files to pickup (receive) from the remote system.

 - All:     For all address.
 - Primary: For primary address only.
 - None:    Do not pick up mail or files at all.


Example:   Pickup=All

@EndNode

@Node "ProcessOnly4D" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/ProcessOnly4D"
@Next "TaskPri"
@Prev "Pickup"
@Toc  "cfgSpeciali"

Name:      ProcessOnly4D=<boolean>

   Send to the remote system only the files with 4D name.

For example: 2.331.106.0.OUT
             2.331.106.0.FLO


Example:   ProcessOnly4D=ON

@EndNode

@Node "TaskPri" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/TaskPri"
@Next ""
@Prev "Pickup"
@Toc  "cfgSpeciali"

Name:      TaskPri=<value>

   Sets the priority of the task.


Example:   TaskPri=0

@EndNode

@Node "cfgSystem" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System"
@Next ""
@Prev "cfgSpeciali"
@Toc  "MailerSettings"

System options
**************

 @{" Accounting " Link "Accounting"}
 @{" AcctMax " Link "AcctMax"}
 @{" Boss " Link "Boss"}
 @{" CallNode " Link "CallNode"}
 @{" CallNumber " Link "CallNumber"}
 @{" DislTimeout " Link "DialTimeout"}
 @{" Flags " Link "Flags"}
 @{" Name " Link "Name"}
 @{" Nodelist " Link "Nodelist"}
 @{" Password " Link "Password"}
 @{" Phone " Link "Phone"}
 @{" Place " Link "Place"}
 @{" RedialDelay " Link "RedialDelay"}
 @{" ResetTimeout " Link "ResetTimeout"}
 @{" Retries " Link "Retries"}
 @{" Ringings " Link "Ringings"}
 @{" Rings " Link "Rings"}
 @{" RingTimeout " Link "RingTimeout"}
 @{" SysOp " Link "SysOp"}

@EndNode

@Node "Accounting" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Accounting"
@Next "AcctMax"
@Prev ""
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      Accounting=<boolean>

   If enabled, GMS_Mailer will keep a database of:

- The number of calls made to a node
- The number of calls received from that node
- The number of successful sessions
- The number of failed sessions
- The number of BUSY results
- The number of NO CARRIER, NO ANSWER results
- The number of VOICE results
- The TrxID value of the last successful session


Example:   Accounting=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "AcctMax" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/AcctMax"
@Next "Boss"
@Prev "Accounting"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      AcctMax=<limiti>

   When accounting is enabled, GMS_Mailer, when instructed to call a certain
node, will check whether or not this node exceeds the accounting limits set
by this keyword.

   The limits parameter, a single string enclosed in quotes, sets:

- The number of calls out
- The number of failed sessions
- The number of BUSY results
- The number of NO CARRIER, NO ANSWER and NO DIALTONE results
- The number of VOICE results


Examples:  AcctMax="50 10 -1 -1 0"
           AcctMax="-1 -1 -1 -1 -1"

@EndNode

@Node "Boss" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Boss"
@Next "CallNode"
@Prev "AcctMax"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      Boss=<addr>

   Specifies the FidoNet address of your boss, as in `2:331/106@fidonet.org'.
Please be careful as not to leave out the zone and point information when
your boss node is capable of four dimensional addressing.

   Note: the setting of <Boss> also specifies what mail will be sent to the
other system when you call out using a telephone number.

   Just to be on the safe side: if you are running a node, set this to your
own address.  


Example:   Boss=2:331/106@fidonet.org

@EndNode

@Node "CallNode" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/CallNode"
@Next "CallNumber"
@Prev "Boss"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      CallNode=<multiaddr>

   With this keyword, GMS_Mailer call a node.

   For use this keyword, nodelist will be present.


Examples:  CallNode=2:331/106@fidonet.org
           CallNode="2:331/106@fidonet.org 2:331/117@fidonet.org"

@EndNode

@Node "CallNumber" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/CallNumber"
@Next "DislTimeout"
@Prev "CallNode"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      CallNumber=<phone-number>

   With this keyword, GMS_Mailer call a node with the phone number.


Example:   CallNumber=0332-706469

@EndNode

@Node "DialTimeout" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/DialTimeout"
@Next "Flags"
@Prev "CallNumber"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      DialTimeout=<seconds>

   Specifies the time in seconds how long GMS_Mailer will wait for a
CONNECT, BUSY, NO CARRIER, VOICE or ERROR response from the modem after
sending a dial command. If the given timeout expires, GMS_Mailer will give
up waiting and re-initialize the modem.


Example:   DialTimeout=30

@EndNode

@Node "Flags" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Flags"
@Next "Name"
@Prev "DialTimeout"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      Flags=<string>

   Are the modem flags that will be send in the EMSI handshake.


Example:   Flags="CM,XX,H16"

@EndNode

@Node "Name" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Name"
@Next "Nodelist"
@Prev "Flags"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      Name=<string>

   Is the name of this system. It will be sent to the remote system during the
session handshake.


Example:   Name="GMS Development"

@EndNode

@Node "Nodelist" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Nodelist"
@Next "Password"
@Prev "Name"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      Nodelist=<string>

   Is the directory that contain the nodelist.


Example:   Nodelist="Mail:Nodelist/"


See also:     @{"CallNode" Link "CallNode"}

@EndNode

@Node "Password" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Password"
@Next "Phone"
@Prev "Nodelist"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      Password=<passwd>

   Specifies the password that will be send to the remote system.


Example:   Password=PASSWD

@EndNode

@Node "Phone" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Phone"
@Next "Place"
@Prev "Password"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      Phone=<phone number>

   Is the phone number that will be send in the EMSI handshake.


Example:   Phone=++39-425-4125

@EndNode

@Node "Place" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Place"
@Next "RedialDelay"
@Prev "Phone"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      Place=<string>

   Is the place of the system that will be send during the EMSI handshake.


Example:   Place=Italy

@EndNode

@Node "RedialDelay" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/RedialDelay"
@Next "ResetTimeout"
@Prev "Place"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      RedialDelay=<seconds>

   This specifies the amount of time GMS_Mailer spends idling between calls
to a system.


Example:   RedialDelay=60

@EndNode

@Node "ResetTimeout" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/ResetTimeout"
@Next "Retries"
@Prev "RedialDelay"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      ResetTimeout=<minutes>

   Using this switch, you can set the time in minutes between automatic
modem resets.


Example:   ResetTimeout=15

@EndNode

@Node "Retries" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Retries"
@Next "Ringings"
@Prev "ResetTimeout"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      Retries=<retries>

   When calling a system, this instructs GMS_Mailer not to exit on a failed
call (eg. line is busy), but to try it thus often again. Between the calls,
GMS_Mailer will spend <RedialDelay> seconds waiting.


Example:   Retries=50

@EndNode

@Node "Ringings" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Ringings"
@Next "Rings"
@Prev "Retries"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      Ringings=<number>

   This is the number of times GMS_Mailer  will allow another system to keep
the phone "ringing" on an outgoing call.


Example:   Ringings=10

@EndNode

@Node "Rings" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Rings"
@Next "RingTimeout"
@Prev "Ringings"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      Rings=<number>

   Number of rings to wait before answering an incoming call.


Example:   Rings=2

@EndNode

@Node "RingTimeout" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/RingTimeout"
@Next "SysOp"
@Prev "Rings"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      RingTimeout=<seconds>

   Is the number of seconds that GMS_Mailer attends for RING message.


Example:   RingTimeout=5

@EndNode

@Node "SysOp" "GMS_Mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/SysOp"
@Next ""
@Prev "RingTimeout"
@Toc  "cfgSystem"

Name:      SysOp=<name>

   Specifies the SysOp name. This string will be sent to the remote system
during the session handshake.


Example:   SysOp="Mirko Viviani"

@EndNode

