@Node "GMS_Mailer" "GMS_Mailer.guide/GMS_Mailer"
@Next "I comandi ARexx"
@Prev "La configurazione"
@Toc "Main"

GMS_Mailer
**********

   With this program you can run a mailer.

   Arguments: CONFIG/M,LINE/N

CONFIG/M:

   Modify some keyword of the MailerSettings configuration.


LINE/S:

   Specifies the phone line of the mailer.


   GMS_Mailer supports also these keys:

 - Esc     Abort currently session
 - Alt-X   Exit from mailer
 - Alt-Q   Same as Alt-X
 - Alt-A   Answer the phone
 - Alt-R   Reset modem


Examples:  GMS_Mailer line 1
           GMS_Mailer CallNode=2:331/106@fidonet.org
           GMS_Mailer line 1 Answer=on

@EndNode

@Node "I comandi ARexx" "GMS_Mailer.guide/ARexx commands"
@Next "Gli script"
@Prev "I programmi eseguibili"
@Toc "Main"

ARexx commands
**************

   All ARexx commands are included in GMS_Mailer_rexx.library, which should
be opened at the beginning of each GMS script with the following instructions:

     signal on error
     signal on syntax
     
     if( ~show( 'l', "gms_mailer_rexx.library" ) ) then
     do
        if( ~addlib( "gms_mailer_rexx.library", 0, -30, 0 ) )then
        do
           say "Could not open gms_mailer_rexx.library"
           exit 10
        end
     end

   GMS stores a few data for each script that asks for its service, but
unfortunately, there's no way for GMS to know when a script ends, so it
cannot automatically free the memory it allocated for that script.
Therefore, you must do it manually (see @{"EMS_FreeScriptData" Link "EMS_FreeScriptData"}), these
instructions at the end of your script:

     call GMS_Mailer_FreeScriptData()
     return 0

   Special care should be taken for the case of a premature and
unexpected script termination due to an error; your script should
include this error-trapping routine:

     error:
     syntax:
     
     error_text = GMS_Mailer_LastError()
     
     if error_text = '' then error_text = rc ErrorText( rc )
     
     say '| ***BREAK: error at' sigl error_text
     
     call GMS_Mailer_FreeScriptData()
     exit rc


 @{" GMS_Mailer_FreeScriptData " Link "GMS_Mailer_FreeScriptData"} 
 @{" GMS_Mailer_LastError " Link "GMS_Mailer_LastError"} 
 @{" GMS_Mailer_Config_Modify " Link "GMS_Mailer_Config_Modify"} 
 @{" GMS_Mailer_Mailer_Alloc " Link "GMS_Mailer_Mailer_Alloc"} 
 @{" GMS_Mailer_Mailer_Free " Link "GMS_Mailer_Mailer_Free"} 
 @{" GMS_Mailer_Mailer_Version " Link "GMS_Mailer_Mailer_Version"} 
 @{" GMS_Mailer_Call_Node " Link "GMS_Mailer_Call_Node"} 
 @{" GMS_Mailer_Call_Number " Link "GMS_Mailer_Call_Number"} 
 @{" GMS_Mailer_Modem_Reset " Link "GMS_Mailer_Modem_Reset"} 
 @{" GMS_Mailer_Session_Abort " Link "GMS_Mailer_Session_Abort"} 
 @{" GMS_Mailer_Session_Quit " Link "GMS_Mailer_Session_Quit"} 
 @{" GMS_Mailer_Status " Link "GMS_Mailer_Status"} 
 @{" GMS_Mailer_Status_Report " Link "GMS_Mailer_Status_Report"} 


   In the command descriptions a few conventions apply:

   * For all commands, the arguments and (possibly) a result are
     listed. When a command returns a result, you should use this
     syntax:

          <result> = <comando>( <argomento>, ... , <argomento> )

     or, in case you do not care at all about the result,

          CALL <comando>( <argomento>, ... , <argomento> )

   * If an argument is enclosed in `[]' brackets, it is optional.

   * If an argument is not enclosed by `<>', the only possible values
     for that argument are the different strings that, separated by a
     (`|'), make up its name.

   * If an argument includes the ``var name'' or ``stem''
     specification, it means it is an indirect argument; you should not
     pass GMS its value, but rather the name of a variable or a stem
     that holds it.


@EndNode

@Node "GMS_Mailer_FreeScriptData" "GMS_Mailer.guide/ARexx commands/GMS_Mailer_FreeScriptData"
@Next "GMS_Mailer_LastError"
@Prev ""
@Toc "I comandi ARexx"

GMS_Mailer_FreeScriptData
-------------------------

   Free all memory of currently script.


@EndNode

